{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:22:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:22:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17862"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17862"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.83,0,0.08,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10576"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115361"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10576"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17862"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24655"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115361"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EChylomicrons transport dietary lipids from the small intestine to peripheral tissues via the bloodstream. After delivering their triglyceride content to tissues, the resulting particles are known as chylomicron remnants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organs is primarily responsible for the uptake and processing of chylomicron remnants?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver","Pancreas","Gallbladder","Adipose tissue","Kidneys"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for the uptake and processing of chylomicron remnants through specific hepatic receptors. These remnant particles are internalised by hepatocytes where their components (cholesterol, phospholipids, and remaining triglycerides) are recycled for various metabolic processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E secretes digestive enzymes and hormones but does not process chylomicron remnants. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E stores and concentrates bile but has no role in lipoprotein metabolism. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is a target for triglyceride deposition from chylomicrons but does not process the remnant particles. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ekidneys\u003C/strong\u003E filter blood and maintain fluid balance but are not involved in chylomicron remnant metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver\u0027s processing of chylomicron remnants is an essential step in maintaining lipid homeostasis and redistributing dietary lipid components throughout the body.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chylomicron remnants are taken up by hepatocytes via specific receptors for processing and recycling of lipid components.","The liver plays a central role in lipid metabolism by processing chylomicron remnants and redistributing their components.","Chylomicron remnants are formed in the bloodstream after lipoprotein lipase removes triglycerides from chylomicrons."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 69; pg. 854","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17862"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:48:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:48:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10576"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115361"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attrib